    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Explicit Advertising</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Marie Schmon letter comments on July 20 article on advertising with gay themes</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''When Intentions Fall Between the Lines'' (July 20):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''When Intentions Fall Between the Lines'' (July 20):</p>
        <p>The real issue here is not whether ads with gay themes should appear in advertising. The real issue is whether any ad is ''fit to print.'' Most of the ads your article showed are great ads: cute, smart and not offensive. However, the Dior ad is ''not fit to print,'' not because it has a gay theme, but because it is inappropriately sexually explicit (or as you said, ''sexually charged'') and in very poor taste.</p>
        <p>MARIE SCHMON  New York</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
